<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Aperture" class="currentChild" href="Aperture">Aperture</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In any optical system, an opening allowing the passage of light, electrons, or other forms of radiation. In photography, the <em>aperture</em> is the hole through which light passes into a camera, the size of which is controlled by the <a title="Diaphragm" href="Diaphragm">diaphragm</a>. (See <a title="Photography" href="Photography">Photography</a>.) An aperture, in this sense, is also known as an <a title="Iris" href="Iris">iris</a>. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
In a <a title="Cathode-Ray Tube" href="Cathode-Ray_Tube">cathode-ray tube</a>, the size of the aperture determines the size and shape of the electron beam. 
</p>
<p id="l5">
In <a title="Screen Printing" href="Screen_Printing">screen printing</a>, the term <em>aperture</em> refers to one specific opening in the mesh screen through which ink passes, also known as a <a title="Mesh Aperture" href="Mesh_Aperture">mesh aperture</a>. (See <a title="Screen Printing" href="Screen_Printing">Screen Printing</a>.) 
</p>
